    "correctIndex": 2,
    "explanation": "Let \\(t=\\sin x\\implies dt=\\cos x\\,dx\\). Limits: \\(0\\to1\\).\n\n\\(\\int_0^1e^t\\,dt=[e^t]_0^1=e-1\\)",
    "name": "Substitution in Definite Integral"
  },
  {
    "id": "m27_item11",
    "text": "If \\(I_n=\\displaystyle\\int_0^{\\pi/2}\\sin^n x\\,dx\\) and \\(I_n=kI_{n-2}\\), then \\(k=\\)",
    "options": [
      "\\(\\dfrac{n}{n-1}\\)",
      "\\(\\dfrac{n-1}{n}\\)",
      "\\(\\dfrac{n+1}{n}\\)",
      "\\(\\dfrac{n}{n+1}\\)"
    ],
    "correctIndex": 1,
    "explanation": "Using IBP on \\(I_n\\): \\(nI_n=(n-1)I_{n-2}\\implies I_n=\\dfrac{n-1}{n}I_{n-2}\\).\n\nSo \\(k=\\dfrac{n-1}{n}\\).",
    "name": "Reduction Formula Coefficient"
  },
  {
    "id": "m27_item12",
    "text": "\\(\\displaystyle\\int_0^{\\pi/4}(\\tan^2x-\\tan^4x)\\,dx=\\)",
    "options": [
      "\\(3\\)",
      "\\(2\\)",
      "\\(\\dfrac{1}{3}\\)",
      "\\(0\\)"
    ],
    "correctIndex": 2,
    "explanation": "\\(\\int_0^{\\pi/4}\\tan^2x(1-\\tan^2x)dx=\\int_0^{\\pi/4}\\tan^2x\\cdot\\sec^2x\\cdot\\dfrac{\\tan^2x-1+\\tan^2x}{\\sec^2x}\\)\n\nSimplify: \\(\\int_0^{\\pi/4}\\sec^2x\\tan^2x\\,dx\\). Let \\(t=\\tan x\\): \\(\\int_0^1t^2dt=\\dfrac{1}{3}\\)",
    "name": "Definite Integral via Substitution"
  },
  {
    "id": "m27_item13",
    "text": "\\(\\displaystyle\\int_0^{\\pi/4}\\tan^2x\\,dx=\\)",
    "options": [
